For example, bulldogs (which have the worst problems with inbreeding, even more than pugs), have a hard time breathing, and even tend to have underbites which make eating very difficult for them. One example of why inbreeding is bad for plants is the potato. When they were first discovered in Peru by Europeans, the Europeans brought two potato plants back to Europe. Up until the Irish Potato Famine, every potato in Europe was a descendent of those two potatoes. What was the cause of the Irish Potato Famine? A rare genetic disease. What can make such diseases more common? As he already said, inbreeding can. Basically, inbreeding is bad all around, unless you manage to avoid the genetic diseases, in which case, the best it gets is just as good as not inbreeding, except a little worse anywhere other than the southern states in America, because anywhere else, people will look down on you.

For those who are wondering about eyes that are hazel, green, etc. Here's your answer

There are only meant to be 2 eye colours (blue and brown), So if you have a different eye colour it means that the code in your genes was messed up, green eyes are just a mutation of brown eyes. Green eyes for example carry the same allele as brown eyes, but it's just a mutation that causes them to appear green. And BTW, if u have green eyes it DOESNT mean you're adopted or your parents had an affair 😂😂 some people actually thought that.

While the facts here are true, there a few misleading omissions in the chosen terminology by strictly sticking to relative risks.

While there's about a 2% risk of birth defects in the general population, first-cousin children have about a 4% chance. Of course, you can phrase that in any number of ways, depending on how you want to spin it. On the one hand, that means that there's double the risk of birth defects in the children of first cousins. On the other hand, 96% of such children are born completely healthy, which is still the vast majority.

As weird as it might sound, third cousin marriages actually might produce healthier offspring than the general population, and further more have an easier time conserving compared the unrelated couple.Based on studies done in iceland.

But.. Mutts aren't healthier. That's a fallacy perpetuated by the "adopt don't shop" agenda. Because of the scientific advances we now have available to us, responsible breeders are testing all their breeding stock to determine whether or not their animals are carriers of the genetic disorders common in their respective breed. Mutts and mixes are generally not tested for anything even if the mix is known, bc running the genetic panels of 2 or more dog breeds on a single dog often proves more expensive and less lucrative than perpetuating the idea that the known unknowns of breeding mutts is somehow safer and healthier. It's really not.

That being said, there are still those who do health test their mixed bred dogs and pups. They are few and will not come cheap. So, one can expect to pay as much for a healthy mutt as they would a healthy purebred dog. But it's worth it to guarantee the health and longevity of your new best friend!
If you're not planning to adopt the first doggo that tugs at your heartstrings(regardless of breed), you should really research breeds and breeders to better acquaint yourself with what is available and what responsible breeders may be in your area.

The problems only start when you have double cousins(people who share BOTH sets of grandparents) or direct family.

In 2nd year Evolution, I've heard a lot on inbreeding v outcrossing. Yes, inbreeding increases the chance of recessive alleles appearing...but that same chance also means that because they pop up more often, they won't hide out in heterozygotes (carriers) as often. Inbreeding gradually removes heterozygotes, and natural selection can then work on the resulting pure individuals (recessive purebreeds die), resulting in more fit individuals. Sounds great... except that removing genetic variation in the population is not favourable if conditions are changing, as it reduces the chance that some individual is able to thrive in the new environment (natural selection can't act on no variation).

Bottom line: inbreeding is best in steady environments, while outcrossing is better in changing environments, at least in the grand scheme of things.

While you were 99% accurate in what you said, it is not 50-50 mom and dad exactly. There is a portion of your genetic code that is randomized every time offspring are created. This is how mutations in the code come about as well as the interaction between the parents' respective chromosomes. Also, while you are correct that inbreeding does not directly cause new mutations, the less genetic diversity that is available for randomization, the statistical probability for dangerous mutations (rather than harmless ones, like red hair) to occur does go up. It's like drawing from a random assortment of 100 different colored beads and the bad mutations are represented by drawing two of the same color family (like sky blue and turquoise); now imagine that there is more of the same colors in the bag you are drawing from, so that there are only 75 or further down the line, 50 different colors. Now the odds of drawing 2 similar colored beads (representative of the dangerous mutation) are much higher. So, preexisting harmful mutations aren't the only danger of inbreeding. While it does not ensure or directly create harmful mutations, it does increase the odds of such occurring.

There is one problem: the amount of potential rare genetic diseases. There are a lot of them. A lot... they don't appear a lot, but it doesn't mean there aren't a lot of types of diseases.

Let's do a math question for a sec: let's say there are a billion possible genetic disorders, and let's say each person have an allele for 50 of them. That means their combine allele pool of gen-disorder is 100 (best case scenario). Now if you have an offspring from a random person, the chance both of you share an allele of a gen-dis is very low. (1/20,000,000^50 according to our example), so we don't to even consider the 1/4 chance. However if you have an offspriger with your sibling, the chance that you share alleles from multiple diseases is much higher (0.000000000289. I know it's a small number but relatively it's much higher than 1/20,000,000^50*), so the 1/4 question might be asked multiple times. And do remember these numbers (Bil diseases, 50 alleles in each person) are made up.

In short, it is much, much much more safer not to entertain the question of incest. That goes double for multi-generational incest...

The paragraph "Is inbreeding ever good? Not so much in humans but..." makes it sound that the other uses are positive, but they really aren't. Our over-reliance on a genetically narrow set of plants in agriculture makes our food supply very susceptible to pathogens.

This happened to the banana Gros Michel that were attacked by what was dubbed the Panama-disease. At the time this was the main banana and it is said that our current banana-flavour in candy closely resembles the flavour of the Gros Michel.

However, the Panama-disease quickly spread across the world's plantations and wiped them out, mainly because genetically they were basically clones, so a pathogen effective on one was effective on all. This forced a switch to our current Cavendish banana, but the Panama-disease is back and has started to infect these as well and it's a real concern. Not because there won't be bananas at the grocery store anymore, though that'd be a shame, but for millions of people banana growing is their main or only source of income, and for millions more it's their main source of calories.

Really? The brown eye genes are dominant? So...why, then, do I have blue eye? Why does ANYONE still have blue eyes? Or green, for that matter? My father has brown eyes and dark brown hair. My mother has blue eyes, and dirty blonde hair. If brown eyes and brown hair are dominant, why am I the rarest of rare combinations of blue eyes and RED hair?

It's something I hear EVERYWHERE. That a certain gene is the dominant or recessive. But I never hear anyone talking about the actual probability of someone not inheriting the dominant genes and instead getting only the recessive ones. And especially for someone like me, my sister and one of our cousins. Out of eight grandchildren, we three are the only redheads.

Which is even more bizarre when you realize that the closest redhead in our family is our grand uncle (our mother's father's brother). And as far as I know, no one of the same generation had red hair. Nor did anyone of the previous generation, either, but I could be wrong about that. I didn't get to even meet either of my great-grandfathers on my mother's side.

And my dad's side is just as weird. My father, being the oldest, has a lighter complexion but almost black hair and dark brown eyes, as does the youngest of the five brothers. The second oldest and second youngest bother have a medium complexion and darker (not dark) brown hair (skin darker and hair lighter than my father), and a lighter brown color of eyes. They're also both the only two to have a receding hair line, as well. And the middle brother has a darker (olive) complexion, but has the lightest hair color of the five brothers, and his eyes are green. He's also the tallest of them as well, if memory serves me right.

Genetics aren't ruled by what is dominant. If they were, EVERYONE would still have darker hair and darker eyes. I would LOVE to see SOMEONE make a video explaining how the PROBABILITY of genetics works, not just the fact that some genes are dominant. But what are the chances of that.

Please, if ANYONE reading this knows of any study or article/post that covers that specific subject, please reply with a link to it.
